'''Peter Victor Ferdinand Cazalet''' (1907-73) was a British [[cricket]]er, jockey, racehorse owner and trainer from [[Shipbourne]], [[Kent]]. He played [[first-class cricket]] for [[Kent County Cricket Club]] and the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]]. He served in the [[Guards Armoured Division]] during the [[Second World War]], reaching the rank of Major. Post-war, he trained many horses owned by [[Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother]] and other notable owners. He was [[British jump racing Champion Trainer]] on three occasions.

==Personal life==
Peter Victor Ferdinand Cazalet was born at [[Fairlawne]], [[Shipbourne]], [[Kent]] on 15 January 1907. He was the third son and youngest child of [[William Marshall Cazalet]] and Maud Cazalet.<ref name=GM/><ref name=Chapman>{{cite book |title=Shipbourne Life and Times |first=Frank |last=Chapman |publisher=Frank Chapman |year=2005 |location=Shipbourne |chapter=The Guvnor's years |pages=3-6}}</ref> His brothers were Edward and [[Victor Cazalet|Victor]]; his sister was [[Thelma Cazalet|Thelma]]. Edward was killed in action in 1916.<ref name=Times251032>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Mr. W. M. Cazalet. |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=25 October 1925 |page_number=9 |issue=46273 |column=D }}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]].<ref name=GM>{{cite journal |url=http://guardsmagazine.com/features_winter15_07Cazelet.html |title=PETER CAZALET A WELSH GUARDSMAN AT WAR |first=Peter |last=Martin |journal=The Guards Magazine |issue=Winter 2015 |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Cazalet was good at racket sports and [[cricket]],<ref name=Chapman/> playing [[lawn tennis]] and [[Rackets (sport)|rackets]].<ref name=Times030822>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Lawn Tennis |day_of_week=Thursday |date=3 August 1922 |page_number=4 |issue=43100 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=Times160225>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Public School Rackets |day_of_week=Monday |date=16 February 1925 |page_number=4 |issue=43887 |column=B }}</ref> Cazalet scored a century in the [[Eton v Harrow]] cricket match at [[Lord's Cricket Ground]] in July 1926.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eton College v Harrow School|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/211/211407.html|website=cricketarchive.com|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref> In September of that year, he played at [[The Oval]] in a match between the Young Amateurs of Kent versus the Young Amateurs of Surrey. He scored 117.<ref name=Times040926>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Young Amateurs at The Oval |day_of_week=Saturday |date=4 sepyember 1926 |page_number=5 |issue=44368 |column=B }}</ref> By May 1928, he was playing for [[Kent County Cricket Club]], scoring 150 against Oxford University. In that match, he scored 204 in a partnership with [[Frank Woolley]], who scored 100. ''The Times'' commented that Cazalet was not even overshadowed by Woolley.<ref name=Times100528>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Kent's Big Score |day_of_week=Thursday |date=10 May 1928 |page_number=7 |issue=44889 |column=C }}</ref> Cazalet was still playing for Kent in 1932.<ref name=Times130632>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Tonbridge Week |day_of_week=Monday |date=13 June 1932 |page_number=5 |issue=46158 |column=B }}</ref> He turned down the chance to captain the club to pursue a career in horse racing.<ref name=Chapman/> Cazalet played in 22 [[First-class cricket|first-class]] matches in the period 1927-32.<ref name=Cricket>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/11069.html |title=Peter Cazalet |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref>

Cazalet's father died on 22 October 1932.<ref name=Times251032/> Shortly afterwards, it was announced that he would marry Leonora Wodehouse,<ref name=Times151132>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Forthcoming Marriages |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=15 November 1932 |page_number=17 |issue=46291 |column=C }}</ref> the stepdaughter of [[P. G. Wodehouse]].<ref name=Chapman/> They were married at [[St Giles' Church, Shipbourne]] on 14 December 1932. His brother Victor was the best man.<ref name=Times151232>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Marriages |day_of_week=Thursday |date=15 December 1932 |page_number=17 |issue=46317 |column=D-E }}</ref> They had a son, [[Edward Cazalet|Edward]], and a daughter, Sheran.<ref name=Chapman/> Leonora died in [[London]] on 16 May 1944 during a routine [[surgery|operation]].<ref name=GM/><ref name=Times170544>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Obituary |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=17 May 1944 |page_number=7 |issue=49858 |column=E }}</ref><ref name=Times230544>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Mrs. Peter Cazalet |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=23 May 1944 |page_number=6 |issue=49863 |column=D }}</ref> Cazalet was given a few days leave to attend her funeral.<ref name=GM/> Leonora was cremated and her ashes were scattered at Fairlawne. A window in St Giles' Church is dedicated to her.<ref name=Chapman/>

In 1949,<ref name=Chapman/> Cazalet married Zara Strutt, the former wife of [[Ronald Strutt, 4th Baron Belper|Lord Belper]],<ref name=Times300573/>and daughter of [[Henry Stapleton Mainwaring, 5th Baronet|Sir Harry Mainwaring]]. They had three sons, although one, David, died in infancy. He is commemorated by a silver cross in St Giles' Church.<ref name=Chapman/> In 1957, Cazalet was nominated for the position of [[High Sheriff of Kent]],<ref name=Times131157>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Nomination of Sheriffs |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=13 November 1957 |page_number=15 |issue=53997 |column=E-F }}</ref> a position to which he was appointed in 1960 .<ref name=Times170360>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The New Sheriffs |day_of_week=Thursday |date=17 March |page_number=19 |issue=54722 |column=D }}</ref> Zara Cazalet died in 2004 at the age of 87.<ref name=Chapman/>

==Pre-war career==
Cazalet started his career as a jockey in [[point-to-point racing]]. He came second on ''Beau Geste'' at the North Cotswold Hunt in April 1929.<ref name=Times180429>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Point-to-Point Races |day_of_week=Thursday |date=18 April 1929 |page_number=6 |issue=45180 |column=F }}</ref> In 1930, he moved up to [[National Hunt racing]]. He rode ''Rocquefort II'' at [[Haydock Park Racecourse|Haydock Park]] in December of that year.<ref name=Times061230>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Racing |day_of_week=Saturday |date=6 December 1930 |page_number=5 |issue=45689 |column=A-D }}</ref> At this time, Cazalet was building a stable of steeplechasers at Fairlawne. They were trained by Harry Whiteman.<ref name=GM/> Cazalet gave [[Elizabeth Taylor]] instruction in horse-riding when she was a girl.<ref name=ET>{{cite web |url=http://www.dameelizabethtaylor.com/animals.html |title=Animals |publisher=The Elizabeth Taylor Archive |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>

Cazalet rode in the [[Grand National]] three times. He rode ''Master Orange'' in 1934,<ref name=Times230334>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Racing |day_of_week=Friday |date=23 March 1934 |page_number=5 |issue=46710 |column=A-E }}</ref> and ''Emancipator'' in 1935 and 1937.<ref name=Times290335>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Liverpool Programme |day_of_week=Friday |date=29 March 1935 |page_number=5 |issue=47025 |column=E-F }}</ref><ref name=Times200337>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Liverpool Results |day_of_week=Saturday |date=20 March 1937 |page_number=5 |issue=47638 |column=C-E }}</ref> In November 1937, Cazalet announced he was to retire from riding as an amateur jockey due to pressures of his business interrests. He was to remain as an owner, with Whiteman continuing to train his horses.<ref name=Times181137>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=(untitled) |day_of_week=Thursday |date=18 November 1937 |page_number=5 |issue=47845 |column=G }}</ref> One of Cazalet's final runners before war broke out was at [[Folkestone Racecourse|Folkestone]], where ''French Beggar'' came third on  on 4 May 1939.<ref name=Times050539>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Folkestone Results |day_of_week=Friday |date=5 May 1939 |page_number=6 |issue=48297 |column=F }}</ref>

==Wartime career==
{{Infobox military person
