Following the outbreak of war in 1939, Cazalet joined the [[Royal Artillery]]. He transferred to the [[Welsh Guards]], along with his friend [[Anthony Bingham Mildmay, 2nd Baron Mildmay of Flete|Anthony Mildmay]]. In 1941, the [[Guards Armoured Division]] was formed under the commande of Sir [[Oliver Leese]] and Cazalet was transferred to the new unit. The Armoured Guards landed at [[Arromanches]], [[Manche]], France on 25 June 1944 and served as a reconnaissance unit during the push across Europe before the German surrender in May 1945.<ref name=GM/> In February 1945, it was reported that Cazalet had been wounded in action.<ref name=Times190245>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Army Casualties |day_of_week=Monday |date=19 Febraury 1945 |page_number=6 |issue=50071 |column=D }}</ref> Both Cazalet and Mildmay were involved in an action at [[Visselh<U+00F6>vede]], [[Lower Saxony]], Germany on the night of 18-19 April 1945 in which they were attacked by German Marines. Cazalet was recommended for the [[Military Medal]] for his part in the action, but it was not awarded. The Guards Armoured Division was disbanded at [[Rotenburg an der W<U+00FC>mme]], Lower Saxony on 9 June 1945.<ref name=GM/>

==Post-war career==
Cazalet started his career as a trainer in November 1945. He paid [[guinea (British coin)|4,000 guineas]] for the five-year-old gelding ''Fisherman{{'}}s Yarn'' at [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]].<ref name=Times031145>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Racing |day_of_week=Saturday |date=3 November 1945 |page_number=2 |issue=50290 |column=G }}</ref> Another of his early horses was ''The Hood'', which was entered for a novice hurdle race at [[Windsor Racecourse|Windsor]] in March 1946.<ref name=Times010346>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename= |day_of_week=Racing |date=1 March 1946 |page_number=2 |issue=50389 |column=D }}</ref> In the 1946-47 season, he had 40 winners, 32 of which were ridden by Mildmay.<ref name=Chapman/>

In 1949, Cazalet and Mildmay stayed at [[Windsor Castle]] as guests of [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth]]. It was during their stay that they persuaded the Queen to buy a [[steeplechase]]r, which Cazalet would train. An early success was ''[[Manicou (horse)|Manicou]]'', which won the [[King George VI Chase]] at [[Kempton Park Racecourse]] in 1950. Another of the Queen's horses trained by Cazalet was ''Monaveen'', which she jointly owned with [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Princess Elizabeth]].<ref name=Times220350>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Queen's Horse |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=22 March 1950 |page_number=3 |issue=51646 |column=D }}</ref> Following Mildmay's death in May 1950, Cazalet inherited the horses owned by Mildmay and [[Pound Sterling|<U+00A3>10,000]].<ref name=Times240650>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Lord Mildmay's Will |day_of_week=Saturday |date=24 June 1950 |page_number=4 |issue=51726 |column=E }}</ref>

Cazalet also trained the Queen Mother's{{ref|a|[Note 1]}} ''[[Devon Loch]]'', which fell on the run-in to the finish line at the 1956 [[Grand National]] when {{convert|50|yd|m}} clear of ''E.S.B.'', which won. ''Devon Loch'' subsequently failed to finish.<ref name=Walwyn/><ref name=Times260356>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Misfortune of Devon Loch in Grand National |day_of_week=Monday |date=26 March 1956 |page_number=4 |issue=53489 |column=A-C }}</ref> His jockey was [[Dick Francis]], who had been designated as Cazalet's first jockey in 1953.<ref name=Francis>{{cite web |url=http://www.broughscott.com/story.asp?NewsID=300 |title=DICK FRANCIS TRIBUTE |first=Brough |last=Scott |authorlink=Brough Scott |publisher=Brough Scott |location=[[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], London |date=21 June 2010 |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>

Cazalet's personal chef for eight years was [[Albert Roux]].<ref name=Chef>{{cite web |url=http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2014/may/18/seven-ages-chef-albert-roux |title=Seven ages of a chef: Albert Roux |publisher=The Guardian |first=John |last=Hind |date=18 May 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Cazalet trained ''Antiar'', which won the Ovaltine Hurdle at [[Fontwell Park Racecourse]] on 22 December 1962, the last day of racing before [[Winter of 1962<U+2013>63 in the United Kingdom|The Big Freeze]] set in. When racing resumed in March 1963, Cazalet had two winners at [[Newbury Racecourse|Newbury]] on 8 March and four the next day.<ref name=Brough>{{cite web |url=http://www.broughscott.com/story.asp?NewsID=2301 |title=The Big Freeze of '63 |first=Brough |last=Scott |authorlink=Brough Scott|publisher=Brough Scott |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> In the 1964-65 season, Cazalet had a record 82 winners.<ref name=GM/> By 1967, he had had his one thousandth winner.<ref name=Chapman/> His final runner was ''Soundless'' at [[Doncaster Racecourse|Doncaster]] on 24 March 1973.<ref name=Times240373>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Doncaster Programme |day_of_week=Saturday |date=24 March 1973 |page_number=6 |issue=58740 |column=A-F }}</ref>

==Death==
Cazalet died at Fairlawne on 29 May 1973.<ref name=Times300573>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Obituary: Mr Peter Cazalet |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=30 May 1973 |page_number=20 |issue=58795 |column=F-H }}</ref> He was buried at St. Giles' Church; four of his jockeys carried his coffin.<ref name=Chapman/> A memorial service was held at the [[Guards Chapel, Wellington Barracks]], [[London]] on 15 June.<ref name=Times020673>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Memorial Services |day_of_week=Saturday |date=2 June 1973 |page_number=26 |issue=58798 |column=C }}</ref> Following his death, [[Fulke Walwyn]] was appointed trainer to the Queen Mother.<ref name=Walwyn>{{cite web |url=http://www.h2g2.com/approved_entry/A735798 |title=The Queen Mother's Passion for Horse Racing |publisher=h2g2 |date=10 June 2002 |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>

Fairlawne was inherited by Edward Cazalet. He was unable to continue the racing stable due to his career as a [[barrister]], and later a High Court judge. In 1979, Fairlawne was sold to racehorse owner [[Khalid ibn Abdullah]].<ref name=Chapman/>

